t may have side effects related to their mechanism of action.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of NSAIDs?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Reduces tumour necrosis factor alpha production","Stabilises lysosomal membranes","Antagonises bradykinin receptors","Inhibits cyclooxygenase enzymes","Blocks substance P release"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ENSAIDs primarily work by \u003Cstrong\u003Einhibiting cyclooxygenase enzymes\u003C/strong\u003E (both COX-1 and COX-2). This reduces the production of prostaglandins, which are key mediators of pain, inflammation, and fever. The patient\u0027s previous gastric ulceration while taking ibuprofen is explained by inhibition of COX-1, which normally maintains protective gastric mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EReduces tumour necrosis factor alpha production\u003C/strong\u003E: while TNF-\u03b1 is an important inflammatory mediator, NSAIDs do not directly affect its production. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStabilises lysosomal membranes\u003C/strong\u003E: this is more characteristic of corticosteroids. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntagonises bradykinin receptors\u003C/strong\u003E: NSAIDs do not directly interact with bradykinin signalling\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBlocks substance P release\u003C/strong\u003E: NSAIDs do not directly affect substance P, which is involved in pain transmission.\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003ECOX-1 is constitutively expressed and maintains normal physiological functions like gastric mucosal protection and platelet function. COX-2 is primarily induced during inflammation. Most traditional NSAIDs inhibit both enzymes, while selective COX-2 inhibitors were developed to reduce gastrointestinal side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-steroidal anti-inflammatory drugs work by inhibiting cyclooxygenase enzymes, reducing prostaglandin synthesis.","Prostaglandins are important mediators of inflammation, pain, and fever.","Cyclooxygenase-1 is constitutively expressed and maintains normal physiological functions, while cyclooxygenase-2 is induced during inflammation."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Available from: https://www.tg.org.au","Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53815"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16653"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"53815","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/53815"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-09T16:27:00+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-09T16:27:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9344"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"68358"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":